Additionally, in order to quantitatively investigate the degradation process, the corresponding degradation data were fitted by the first order kinetic model [27,39,40]: −ln(C/Co
                        ) = kt. In general, the apparent rate constant (k) is proportional to the reaction rate, and can be employed to compare the photocatalytic efficiency for the different photocatalyst [41]. Fig. 4c illustrated the linearities of −ln(C/Co
                        ) vs illumination time t, and the k values and correlation coefficient (R2
                        ) for the prepared samples were listed in Fig. 4d and Table S1, respectively. From Fig. 4c, it was clear to see that the good linear relationship between -ln(C/Co) and illumination time (t) evidenced the applicability of this model. Distinctly, the k values (Fig. 4d) of the different photocatalysts could be ranked as follow: CeO2(40 wt%)/Zn3V2O8 ＞ CeO2(30 wt%)/Zn3V2O8 ＞ CeO2(50 wt%)/Zn3V2O8 ＞ CeO2(20 wt%)/Zn3V2O8 ＞ CeO2(10 wt%)/Zn3V2O8 ＞ Zn3V2O8 ＞ CeO2, which was well in accordance with the results of photocatalytic performances. Notably, the prepared CeO2(40 wt%)/Zn3V2O8 hybrid owned the largest k value with 1.13 × 10−2 min−1, which was approximately 8.1 and 3.8 folds as high as bare CeO2 (0.14 × 10−2 min−1) and Zn3V2O8 (0.30 × 10−2 min−1), respectively, further illustrated that the constructed CeO2/Zn3V2O8 Z-scheme heterojunction was beneficial to improve the photocatalytic activity. Besides, as listed in Table S2, it was observed that the prepared CeO2/Zn3V2O8 hybrid illustrated the superior photocatalytic activity towards TC degradation with shorter degradation time and less photocatalyst dosage than several reported composite photocatalysts. More interestingly, as could be seen from Table S3, compared to recent reported CeO2 and Zn3V2O8-based composite photocatalysts, it was satisfactory that the prepared CeO2/Zn3V2O8 hybrid showed the excellent photocatalytic performance. These results demonstrated that the resulting CeO2/Zn3V2O8 hybrid could be used as a fascinating visible-light-response photocatalyst for the removal of antibiotics from wastewater.
